<codeBook xmlns="ddi:codebook:2_5" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="ddi:codebook:2_5 https://ddialliance.org/Specification/DDI-Codebook/2.5/XMLSchema/codebook.xsd" version="2.5"><docDscr><citation><titlStmt><titl>Effects of news coverage on a victim's character during a crisis (SUF edition)</titl><IDNo agency="DOI">doi:10.11587/YRJZC8</IDNo></titlStmt><distStmt><distrbtr source="archive">AUSSDA</distrbtr><distDate>2022-12-22</distDate></distStmt><verStmt source="archive"><version date="2025-12-18" type="RELEASED">1</version></verStmt><biblCit>Einwiller, Sabine; Laufer, Dan, 2022, "Effects of news coverage on a victim's character during a crisis (SUF edition)", https://doi.org/10.11587/YRJZC8, AUSSDA, V1, UNF:6:g76LI7KWk+NHzZoV98Gpyw== [fileUNF]</biblCit></citation></docDscr><stdyDscr><citation><titlStmt><titl>Effects of news coverage on a victim's character during a crisis (SUF edition)</titl><altTitl>Wirkungen der Berichterstattung über den Charakter eines Opfers während einer Krise</altTitl><IDNo agency="DOI">doi:10.11587/YRJZC8</IDNo></titlStmt><rspStmt><AuthEnty affiliation="University of Vienna">Einwiller, Sabine</AuthEnty><AuthEnty affiliation="Victoria University Wellington">Laufer, Dan</AuthEnty><othId role="Researcher">Neureiter, Ariadne</othId></rspStmt><prodStmt><grantNo agency="University of Vienna">n/a</grantNo></prodStmt><distStmt><distrbtr source="archive">AUSSDA</distrbtr><distrbtr>The Austrian Social Science Data Archive</distrbtr><contact affiliation="The Austrian Social Science Data Archive" email="info@aussda.at">AUSSDA</contact><depositr>Einwiller, Sabine</depositr></distStmt><holdings URI="https://doi.org/10.11587/YRJZC8"/></citation><stdyInfo><subject><keyword xml:lang="en">Social Sciences</keyword><keyword vocab="ELSST" vocabURI="https://elsst.cessda.eu/id">Communications</keyword><keyword vocab="ELSST" vocabURI="https://elsst.cessda.eu/id">Journalism</keyword><keyword vocab="ELSST" vocabURI="https://elsst.cessda.eu/id">Public relations</keyword><topcClas vocab="CESSDA Topic Classification" vocabURI="https://vocabularies.cessda.eu/vocabulary/TopicClassification">Media</topcClas><topcClas vocab="CESSDA Topic Classification" vocabURI="https://vocabularies.cessda.eu/vocabulary/TopicClassification">Public relations</topcClas><topcClas vocab="CESSDA Topic Classification" vocabURI="https://vocabularies.cessda.eu/vocabulary/TopicClassification">Information society</topcClas><topcClas vocab="CESSDA Topic Classification" vocabURI="https://vocabularies.cessda.eu/vocabulary/TopicClassification">Social behaviour and attitudes</topcClas></subject><abstract>Full edition for scientific use. The research addresses the question how reporting of irrelevant information on a crisis victim’s bad character impacts on empathy towards the victim, the victim’s reputation as well as the reputation of the news medium that published the information. This was analyzed by means of a one-factorial experiment with manipulating the reporting on the crisis victim’s character plus a control condition. Respondents (registered members of an online panel) were 245 consumers from the United Kingdom.</abstract><sumDscr><collDate cycle="P1" event="start" date="2021-10-18">2021-10-18</collDate><collDate cycle="P1" event="end" date="2021-10-22">2021-10-22</collDate><nation>United Kingdom</nation><anlyUnit>Individual</anlyUnit><universe>Consumers in the United Kingdom 18+</universe><dataKind>Numeric</dataKind></sumDscr></stdyInfo><method><dataColl><timeMeth>Cross-section</timeMeth><sampProc>Non-probability: Respondent-assisted</sampProc><collMode>Web-based experiment</collMode><resInstru>Questionnaire</resInstru><sources><dataSrc>Population group</dataSrc></sources></dataColl><notes>Additional Information on Sampling: 245 consumers from the UK. Age from 18 to 88 years (M = 45.73, SD = 16.38), 48.6 percent  female, 51 percent male; 0.4 percent (n=1) other</notes><anlyInfo/></method><dataAccs><setAvail/><use